	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Poultry imports cause growing concern in Ghana</h1>

			
			<h4>
												12 November 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In August, <i>Ghana Business News</i> reported that over 200,000 tonnes of frozen chicken imports had come into Ghana from the EU, US and Brazil. In 2002, imports totalled only 26,000 tonnes, mainly from the EU, with this rising to 50,000 tonnes in 2005. Ghana is reported to be importing ‘almost one-third of the EU’s total frozen chicken that goes to Africa’.</p><p>At a recent debate on chicken imports, Ghanaian poultry farmers ‘expressed their dissatisfaction with the status quo, blaming government for letting the poultry industry down’. According to press reports, ‘farmers argued that the country seems to be clueless about how to save the industry’, with parliamentary legislation to increase taxes on poultry imports being blocked by the executive arm of government.</p><p>Speakers from Third World Network Africa maintained that the government was pursuing ‘policies which create opportunity to import poultry’, and that this is given ‘greater weight than policies which stimulate local production’. The situation has been made more acute by the escalating costs of poultry feed and credit, and farmers called on the government to rethink its policy on the poultry sector.</p><p>In response, Ghana’s Deputy Minister of Agriculture, Dr Tia Alfred Sugri, said that ‘the government is finding ways to use tariff and non-tariff measures to restrict the importation of chicken into the country.’ On 21 July, at the biennial conference of the Ghana Society of Animal Production, the deputy minister had called for ‘heavy investment … in the country’s livestock and poultry sectors’.</p><p>USDA analysis suggests that among ACP countries, South Africa and Angola are the major target markets for rising Brazilian broiler chicken meat exports. In the first six months of 2010, some 126,798 tonnes were exported to these two markets, some 7.4% of total Brazilian chicken meat exports and a volume almost equivalent (99.5%) to the volume of Brazilian chicken meat exports to the EU market. In the first six months of 2011, exports to South Africa and Angola had risen 11% to 140,980 tonnes, with the strongest growth being to Angola (from 31,646 to 40,054 tonnes, compared to a rise from 95,152 to 100,926 tonnes for South Africa). South African is the sixth most important destination for Brazilian chicken meat export, while Angola ranks eleventh.</p><p>Brazilian turkey meat exports, which are only 5% of the volume of chicken meat exports, show a different pattern of exports, with African markets being more important and more diversified. While South Africa is the main African market, turkey meat is also exported to Angola, Benin, Congo, DRC, Gabon and Equatorial Guinea. Together these markets accounted for a quarter of Brazilian turkey meat exports in the first six months of 2010 (20,093 tonnes), and over a third in the first six months of 2011.</p><p>Press reports suggest that the high value of the Brazilian Real may be slowing down the rate of expansion of Brazilian poultry meat exports.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
