<a href="http://www.themeatsite.com/meatnews/15192/brazilian-chicken-exports-up-three-per-cent" target="_self">http://www.themeatsite.com/meatnews/15192/brazilian-chicken-exports-up-t...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The EU remains the principal exporter of frozen poultry meat to Ghana. However Brazilian poultry exporters are increasingly focusing on new markets in Africa. While broiler meat exports are focusing on South Africa and Angola, Brazilian exporters are expanding further, developing markets for turkey meat exports in Central and West Africa.</p><p>Given this background, it is essential that any policy aimed at supporting local poultry production is comprehensive in the tariff and non-tariff measures that are set in place, particularly in view of the inherent cost advantages that Brazilian exporters enjoy arising from the ready access to poultry feed (maize and soybean meal). However, as experience elsewhere in West Africa illustrates (90% of Benin’s poultry meat imports are reportedly re-exported to Nigeria), the pursuit of purely national tariff protection measures can give rise to extensive smuggling of poultry parts, which not only undermine national trade policy but also pose serious threats to consumer health. In view of this scenario, there would appear to be a need for coordination of poultry sector trade policies at the regional level in West Africa.</p><p>Ultimately policies will be required that improve the productivity of poultry production (via better disease control systems and improved breeding stock) and which get to grips with the issue of the rising prices of poultry feed inputs. In the absence of effective measures in these areas, the danger arises that temporary protection measures become a permanent feature of poultry sector trade policy, leading to a loss of efficiency and increasing costs to consumers.</p>
		</div>
		
